    "X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, test_size = 0.2, stratify = y, random_state = 1)\n",
    "# If we not put random_state, we will not get the same result, because it can be splitted from anywhere in the dataset, so all the process that needs randomness\n",
    "# It splits your data into: X_train → Training features, X_test → Testing features, y_train → Training target, & y_test → Testing target\n",
    "# train_test_split(X, y): It takes: X → Input features & y → Target labels. And splits them into training and testing sets.\n",
    "# test_size=0.2: 20% is test data\n",
    "# stratify=y (VERY IMPORTANT STEP): It ensures an uniform distribution in both train and test sets.\n",
    "          # Example if origal dataset contains 70% good & 30% bad\n",
    "                        # without stratify: train might become 80% Good & Test might become 60% Good. This causes imbalance problems.\n",
    "                        # with stratify: Train → 70% Good, 30% Bad & Test → 70% Good, 30% Bad\n",
    "# random_state = 1: This ensures same split every time you run the code.\n",
    "         # Without this, data split changes every run whenever any new data or run different time, it affects model accuracy"
   ]
  },
