   "source": [
    "# Let's create a helper function to train tune and evaluate the models\n",
    "# Lets import tree based models\n",
    "from sklearn.tree import DecisionTreeClassifier \n",
    "# Splits data into branches. Makes decisions based on conditions & look alike a flowchart\n",
    "from sklearn.ensemble import RandomForestClassifier, ExtraTreesClassifier\n",
    "# These are ensemble models. Ensemble = Many trees combined together.\n",
    "      # RandomForestClassifier: Builds many trees. Each tree gives prediction. Final answer = Majority vote\n",
    "      # ExtraTreesClassifier: Similar to RandomForest but: Splits more randomly. Can reduce variance further\n",
    "from xgboost import XGBClassifier\n",
    "# XGBoost (very important model): It builds trees sequentially and each new tree corrects previous errors.\n",
    "from sklearn.metrics import accuracy_score\n",
    "# It's used to evaluate model performance. If model predicts 90 correctly out of 100: Accuracy = 90%\n",
    "from sklearn.model_selection import GridSearchCV # It is used for hyperparameter tuning.\n",
    "# Instead of manually trying values for max_depth, min_samples_split, & criterion:\n",
    "      # GridSearchCV: Tries all combinations. Uses cross-validation. Finds best parameters automatically"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "6ff3e7f2",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Simple Analogy\n",
    "DecisionTree → One decision maker\n",
    "\n",
    "RandomForest → Group of decision makers voting\n",
    "\n",
    "ExtraTrees → Even more random group voting\n",
    "\n",
    "XGBoost → Smart decision makers correcting mistakes\n",
    "\n",
    "accuracy_score → Exam result\n",
    "\n",
    "GridSearchCV → Finding best study strategy"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 109,
   "id": "2733a442",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# Lets define a function at one time to avoid repetition of codes\n",
    "def train_model(model, param_grid, X_train, y_train, X_test, y_test):\n",
    "    # model → ML algorithm (DecisionTree, RF, etc.), param_grid → hyperparameters to tune\n",
    "    # X_train, y_train → training data, & X_test, y_test → testing data\n",
    "    grid = GridSearchCV(model, param_grid, cv = 5, scoring = \"accuracy\", n_jobs = -1)\n",
    "    # Now we are going to initialize the grid inside the function grid search cross validation & pass the model\n",
    "    # model: The ML algorithm you passed. param_grid: Dictionary of parameters to try. Eg: {\"max_depth\": [3,5,7]}\n",
    "    # cv=5: 5-fold cross-validation. Training data split into 5 parts --> Model trains 5 times --> Each time different validation fold\n",
    "    # --> Average performance calculated\n",
    "    # scoring=\"accuracy\": Use accuracy to decide best parameters.\n",
    "    # n_jobs=-1: Use all CPU cores → Faster training.\n",
    "    grid.fit(X_train, y_train) # train the model here\n",
    "    # Tries all parameter combinations. Performs cross-validation. & Finds best hyperparameters\n",
    "    best_model = grid.best_estimator_ # find the best model here using best estimator\n",
    "    # This gives: The best trained model with optimal parameters\n",
    "    y_pred = best_model.predict(X_test) # Now model predicts on unseen test data.\n",
    "    acc = accuracy_score(y_test, y_pred) # This calculates: Correct Predictions / Total Predictions\n",
    "    return best_model, acc, grid.best_params_ # This return: The trained best model. Its test accuracy. Best estimator (same as best_model here)\n",
    "\n",
    "# Now the function is ready"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "f9619f77",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### The above train_model function: \n",
    "So instead of repeating code for every model (DecisionTree, RF, XGB), you have created one reusable function\n",
    "\n",
    "1️⃣ Takes a model\n",
    "\n",
    "2️⃣ Tunes it using GridSearchCV\n",
    "\n",
    "3️⃣ Trains it\n",
    "\n",
    "4️⃣ Predicts on test data\n",
    "\n",
    "5️⃣ Calculates accuracy\n",
    "\n",
    "6️⃣ Returns the best model + accuracy"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 110,
   "id": "680c2289",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "dt = DecisionTreeClassifier(random_state = 1, class_weight = \"balanced\")\n",
    "# Here, we are Initializing a Decision Tree, Handling class imbalance, & Defining hyperparameters for tuning\n",
    "# random_state=1: This ensures: The model behaves the same way every time you run it. Tree splits exactly same as before\n",
    "# class_weight=\"balanced\": This handles class imbalance. If the risk dataset has 70% good , normally model may favor good class.\n",
    "# This automatically gives more importance to minority class & Penalizes mistakes on minority/majority class more. This improves fairness.\n",
    "# Lets define a dictionary like max_depth\n",
    "dt_param_grid = {\n",
    "    \"max_depth\": [3, 5, 7, 10, None], # How deep the tree can grow.\n",
    "    # Smaller depth → Simple tree → Less overfitting. Larger depth → Complex tree → Risk of overfitting\n",
    "    # None → Grow fully until pure leaves. \n",
    "    # Example: max_depth=3 → Very simple model & max_depth=None → Very complex model\n",
    "    \"min_samples_split\": [2, 5, 10], # Minimum number of samples required to split a node.\n",
    "    # If set to 2 → Split even small groups & If set to 10 → Node must have at least 10 samples to split\n",
    "    # Higher value: Reduces overfitting & Makes tree smoother\n",
    "    \"min_samples_leaf\": [1, 2, 4] # Minimum samples required in a leaf node.\n",
    "    # If set to: 1 → Leaf can contain 1 sample & 4 → Leaf must contain at least 4 samples\n",
    "    # Higher value: Makes model more stable & Prevents tiny noisy leaves\n",
    "}"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "d61e755c",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### What GridSearchCV Will Do\n",
    "\n",
    "It will try all combinations: 5 (max_depth options) × 3 (min_samples_split options) × 3 (min_samples_leaf options)= 45 combinations\n",
    "\n",
    "With 5-fold cross validation: 45 × 5 = 225 model trainings. Then it selects the best one.\n",
    "\n",
    "Here you are tunning a model with different tree heights, different splitting rules, & different minimum gropu sizes.\n",
    "Then choose the best configuration."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 111,
   "id": "d062c764",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# Now lets call the best decision tree, accuracy decision tree, & parameter decision tree\n",
    "best_dt, acc_dt, params_dt = train_model(dt, dt_param_grid, X_train, y_train, X_test, y_test)\n",
    "# Here we calling the function you created earlier to train and tune your Decision Tree\n",
    "\n",
    "# train_model(...): This is the function you defined earlier. \n",
    "# - Runs GridSearchCV\n",
    "# - Finds best hyperparameters\n",
    "# - Trains best model\n",
    "# - Predicts on test set\n",
    "# - Calculates accuracy\n",
    "\n",
    "# dt: inputs we passed: our DecisionTreeClassifier object.\n",
    "\n",
    "# dt_param_grid: Dictionary of hyperparameters to test. GridSearch will try different combinations.\n",
    "\n",
    "# X_train, y_train: Used to train the model and tune hyperparameters.\n",
    "\n",
    "# X_test, y_test: Used to evaluate final model performance."
   ]
  },
